# Lesson 6-4 — Solving Absolute Value Inequalities

Source: (Module 6, Lesson 6-4, Int1_0604_practice.docx)

## Today's Goals

* Solve absolute value inequalities and rewrite them as compound inequalities using *and* or *or*
* Graph the solution set of an absolute value inequality on a number line
* Model real-world situations with absolute value inequalities and interpret the solutions
* Recognize special cases where an absolute value inequality has no solution or all real numbers as solutions

## Vocabulary

* **absolute value inequality** — An inequality that contains an absolute value expression, such as [|x - 3| < 5].
* **compound inequality** — Two inequalities joined by the word *and* or *or*.
* **solution set** — The set of all values that make an inequality true.
* **margin of error** — The maximum allowable difference between a measured or claimed value and the actual value.
* **open sentence** — A mathematical statement that contains a variable and becomes true or false when values are substituted.

## Learn: Solving Absolute Value Inequalities

An absolute value inequality can be rewritten as a compound inequality. The direction of the inequality symbol and the sign of the right-hand side determine the form of the compound inequality.

### Key Concept: Rewriting Absolute Value Inequalities

* If [|X| < a] and [a > 0], rewrite as [-a < X < a] (compound inequality with *and*).
* If [|X| \le a] and [a > 0], rewrite as [-a \le X \le a] (compound inequality with *and*).
* If [|X| > a] and [a > 0], rewrite as [X < -a] or [X > a] (compound inequality with *or*).
* If [|X| \ge a] and [a > 0], rewrite as [X \le -a] or [X \ge a] (compound inequality with *or*).
* If [a < 0] and the symbol is [<] or [\le], there is **no solution** because absolute value is never negative.
* If [a < 0] and the symbol is [>] or [\ge], the solution is **all real numbers** because absolute value is always non-negative.

## Example 1 — Solve Less-Than Absolute Value Inequalities

Solve absolute value inequalities with less-than or less-than-or-equal-to symbols, then graph the solution set on a number line.

### Step 1: Identify the Form

Determine whether the inequality uses [<] or [\le] and whether the right-hand side is positive or negative.

For [|x + 8| < 16]:
[
-16 < x + 8 < 16
]

### Step 2: Solve the Compound Inequality

Isolate the variable in the middle by subtracting or adding the same value to all three parts.

[
-16 - 8 < x < 16 - 8
]
[
-24 < x < 8
]

For inequalities with a coefficient on the variable inside the absolute value, such as [|2c - 1| \le 7]:
[
-7 \le 2c - 1 \le 7
]
[
-6 \le 2c \le 8
]
[
-3 \le c \le 4
]

### Step 3: Graph the Solution

Graph the solution set on a number line using open or closed circles depending on the inequality symbol.

## Example 2 — Solve Greater-Than Absolute Value Inequalities

Solve absolute value inequalities with greater-than or greater-than-or-equal-to symbols, then graph the solution set on a number line.

### Step 1: Identify the Form

Determine whether the inequality uses [>] or [\ge] and whether the right-hand side is positive or negative.

For [|r + 2| > 6]:
[
r + 2 < -6 \quad \text{or} \quad r + 2 > 6
]

### Step 2: Solve Each Inequality

Solve each part of the compound inequality separately.

[
r < -8 \quad \text{or} \quad r > 4
]

For inequalities with a coefficient, such as [|2h - 3| \ge 9]:
[
2h - 3 \le -9 \quad \text{or} \quad 2h - 3 \ge 9
]
[
2h \le -6 \quad \text{or} \quad 2h \ge 12
]
[
h \le -3 \quad \text{or} \quad h \ge 6
]

### Step 3: Graph the Solution

Graph both parts of the solution on a number line. The solution is the union of the two intervals.

## Example 3 — Real-World Applications

Write and solve absolute value inequalities that model real-world situations involving tolerance, margin of error, or acceptable ranges.

### Step 1: Translate the Situation

Identify the target value and the allowable deviation from that value.

For a speedometer accurate within [\pm 2.5\%] at 60 mph:
[
|s - 60| \le 0.025(60)
]
[
|s - 60| \le 1.5
]

### Step 2: Solve and Interpret

Solve the inequality and interpret the result in the context of the problem.

[
-1.5 \le s - 60 \le 1.5
]
[
58.5 \le s \le 61.5
]

The car could actually be traveling between 58.5 mph and 61.5 mph.

Other situations include baking temperatures within a range, paint amounts within a tolerance, healthy weight ranges, and SAT scores within standard deviations of the mean.

## Example 4 — Special Cases

Recognize and explain absolute value inequalities that have no solution or all real numbers as solutions.

### No Solution

When the right-hand side is negative and the symbol is [<] or [\le], the inequality has no solution because an absolute value can never be less than a negative number.

[
|m + 4| < -2 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \text{no solution}
]

[
\left|\frac{7c + 3}{2}\right| \le -5 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \text{no solution}
]

### All Real Numbers

When the right-hand side is negative and the symbol is [>] or [\ge], the solution is all real numbers because an absolute value is always non-negative.

[
|5v + 3| > -9 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \text{all real numbers}
]

[
\left|\frac{2g + 3}{2}\right| > -7 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \text{all real numbers}
]

## Example 5 — Fractional Coefficients and Mixed Practice

Solve more complex absolute value inequalities that include fractional expressions or negative coefficients inside the absolute value, then graph each solution set.

### Fractional Expressions

For inequalities such as [\left|\frac{3h + 1}{2}\right| < 8]:
[
-8 < \frac{3h + 1}{2} < 8
]
[
-16 < 3h + 1 < 16
]
[
-17 < 3h < 15
]
[
-\frac{17}{3} < h < 5
]

### Negative Coefficients

For inequalities such as [|-6r - 4| < 8], first isolate the absolute value, then proceed as usual. The negative coefficient does not change the solving process.

[
-8 < -6r - 4 < 8
]
[
-4 < -6r < 12
]

Remember to reverse the inequality symbols when dividing by a negative number:
[
\frac{2}{3} > r > -2 \quad \text{or} \quad -2 < r < \frac{2}{3}
]

